 analyze the ways people used these writings to reinforce their beliefs about citizenship and presidential leadership in the United States, with specific attention to the fissure between republicanism and democracy that still exists today. Their study employs rhetorical and corpus research methods to assess more than five hundred reminiscences.A novel look at how memories of Lincoln became an important form of political rhetoric, this book sheds light on how divergent schools of U.S. political thought came to recruit Lincoln as their standard-bearer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh1 aKaufer, David S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079981zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271079981/original  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK